<TITLE> Stocks soar higher </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 25 (bdnews24.com)Markets heated up on Monday for a second straight day, paced by a buying spree in insurance, non-bank financial institutions and ICT shares. Dhaka stocks started rising on the opening bell and continued with the trend until the midday session before profit-taking led the indices onto a downward curve. DSE's benchmark general index or DGEN gained 13.64 points or 0.53 percent to close at 2584.23. The DSI or all share price index finished at 2149.58, up by 10.55 points or 0.49 percent. The blue-chip DSE-20 rose 21.87 points or 1.11 percent to end on 1976.43. Of the traded scrips, 124 advanced, 107 declined and five remained unchanged. Market experts said the rally of NBFIs, insurance and IT issues pulled the market up. The sectors performed well in the last week, as well. "Investors opted for NBFIs on the news of its coming under BASEL- II framework as per the central bank directive, leading to an increase of the capital base," said Salahuddin Ahmed, a former DSE chief executive. Insurance companies would also see a rise in their authorised capital once the new Insurance Act is in force, added Ahmed who new teaches finance at the University of Dhaka. Market drivers, banks, did not move much along with power issues. Mutual funds ended mixed while fuel and energy shares fell, with ICT shares continuing to rise. Most of the scrips in pharmaceuticals lost except some rising on reports of attractive dividend declarations. Turnover on the country's premier bourse slumped to Tk 4.10 billion from Tk 5.75 billion on Sunday. Beximco Ltd. and Bangladesh Online Ltd. in separate meetings have resolved to hold a meeting of the shareholders, whose name appeared in the share registry on May 24, on June 18, for transferring shares, according to a post on the DSE website. A High Court order on Sunday approved a draft scheme of a merger between Bangladesh Online Ltd. (Transferor) and Beximco Ltd. (Transferee), recommending exchange of 2.82 ordinary shares of the transferor company for 1 ordinary share of transferee company. Summit Power came out as the turnover leader with shares worth Tk 387.458 million traded. It finished at Tk 1291.75, edging up 0.83 percent. Eastern Housing Ltd followed with a turnover of Tk 200.118 million, losing 1.82 percent to end on 765.75. S Alam Cold Rolled Steels ended on Tk 805.75, slipping 0.06 percent. It had shares worth Tk 194.436 million changing hands. Lanka Bangla Finance had Tk 175.856 million in turnover and ended on Tk 224.90, down by 1.14 percent on profit taking. Market major Square Pharmaceuticals saw Tk 153.341 million worth shares traded; it continued to rise form the previous day to close at Tk 3089, rising 3.51 percent. Among the other scrips on the turnover board Titas Gas, Summit Alliance Port Ltd and Fu Wang Ceramicsfell on sell-offs. Bangladesh Industrial Finance Company (BIFC) witnessed gains due to buying pressure. Indices of the Chittagong Stock Exchange also finished upbeat by gains in ICT, insurers and NBFIs. The CSCX or selective categories index rose by 27.39 points or 0.50 percent to close at 5495.05. The CASPI or all share price index ended on 8471.72, gaining 37.91 points or 0.44 percent. The CSE-30 blue chip went up by 21.40 points or 0.33 percent to finish at 6476.57. Gainers edged out losers by 77 to 72 and four scrips held steady. Turnover on the port city bourse crept down to Tk 449.865 million form Sunday's Tk 478.700 million. Summit Power topped the turnover board, with shares of Tk 31.09 million changing hands. Square Pharmaceutricals, Eastern Housing Ltd, Eastern Housing Ltd, Lanka Bangla Finance and Titas Gas were the other turnover leaders.
